        "caption": "FIG 1.0 — THE CANVAS",
        "body_text": "<p>There is a quiet tyranny in the modern ceiling grid. The recessed can light, ubiquitous in construction since the late 1990s, was invented for offices, factories, and hospitals—places of hyper-vigilance, not sanctuaries of rest. It provides what lighting designers call \"general illumination\"—a flat, shadowless wash that ensures you can see the floor, but feel absolutely nothing.</p>",
