        "image": "shopify://shop_images/custom_na1no-banana-pro_1765703436255.png",
        "image_mobile": "shopify://shop_images/custom_nano-banana-pro_1765703436255.png",
        "caption": "FIG 1.1 — CORTISOL CONNECTION",
        "body_text": "<p>It starts with ancient wiring deep within the eye, specifically a receptor known as the melanopsin ganglion cell. Unlike your other optical sensors, this receptor is not interested in vision or detail; it is interested in <em>time</em>. Its primary evolutionary function is to track the position of the sun. When it detects high-intensity, cool-spectrum light beaming from directly overhead—the angle of the sun at noon—it registers a signal to be alert, immediately suppressing melatonin and spiking cortisol. By relying on overhead recessed lighting in the evening, we are accidentally simulating a perpetual \"solar noon,\" placing our bodies in a state of subtle, constant hyper-vigilance just as we are trying to unwind.<br/><br/></p>",
        "body_text_2": "<p>By moving light to the perimeter (walls) and lower planes (tables, floors), you expand the perceived size of the room and highlight the texture of your furnishings, while signaling to your body that the day is done.</p>",
